aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident in Naples, Florida
The accident occurred in Naples, Florida.
The accident occurred on September 17, 2019, at 10:30 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Cessna 152.
The defining event was abnormal runway contact.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Instructional.
The accident number was GAA19CA556.
The aircraft registration was N472TC.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There was 1 person with no injuries in the accident.
The student pilot reported the airplane suddenly sank while on approach to land.
The student pilot added power after the airplane sank.
The airplane bounced after the student pilot added power.
The student pilot added more power after the first bounce.
The airplane bounced again after more power was added.
The nose landing gear collapsed after the second bounce.
The airplane sustained substantial damage to the left wing.
The flight school's chief executive officer reported there were no preaccident mechanical failures with the airplane.
The flight school's chief executive officer reported there were no preaccident mechanical malfunctions with the airplane that would have precluded normal operation.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be the student pilot's improper landing flare.
The improper landing flare resulted in a porpoised landing.
The porpoised landing resulted in a nose landing gear collapse.
The findings included aircraft landing flare not being attained/maintained.
The findings included personnel issues related to aircraft control by the student/instructed pilot.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Naples, Florida

## Date & Time: 
September 17, 2019, 10:30 Local

## Aircraft:
Cessna 152

## Defining Event:
Abnormal runway contact

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Instructional

## Accident Number:
GAA19CA556

## Registration:
N472TC

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis

The student pilot reported that, while on approach to land, the airplane suddenly sank. She added power, but the airplane bounced. She added more power, but the airplane bounced again, and the nose landing gear collapsed. The airplane sustained substantial damage to the left wing. The flight school's chief executive officer reported that there were no preaccident mechanical failures or malfunctions with the airplane that would have precluded normal operation.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:

The student pilot's improper landing flare, which resulted in a porpoised landing and a nose landing gear collapse.

## Findings

| | |
|-|-|
| Aircraft | Landing flare - Not attained/maintained |
| Personnel issues | Aircraft control - Student/instructed pilot |
